Affordable price for great food. They have large space  for outside dining, you can choose to sit somewhere away from other customers. The food was delicious!

These guys are serving dim sum in the morning and early afternoon! It was so great to be able to have some again! Egg custard buns and the pork bun was lovely.  They have a great picture menu and most staff speak English (or at least some english). So glad they are back open!

I ordered tofu and fish over rice and the wait wasn't long! The food was delicious and reasonably priced. They also have outdoor seating, one of the few in the area! Would definitely go there again. They also have their menus so even if you don't speak chinese, you can point at what you want.
good

We were craving dim sum despite the pandemic and this was a great place to get it. They have outdoor seating the tables are at least 6 ft apart. At the time we went there was no one there. The dumplings were generously sized. I recommend the Har gow, the steamed rice rolls, and the pork and leek dumplings. The staff was very gracious.
Steam Alaska King Crab

Normally this is a very cheap dim sum place, but when I went today, the food was sour, and the staff didn’t have good customer service. When I paid less than 15% tip for their bad service, they literally chased me out the door to beg for money.

Food is generally decent - probably most popular for their large Alaskan/King crabs. Some months, you get lucky and it's 28/lb, but standard prices are usually 33/lb. Plenty of stellar seafood options, but non-seafood options are also good. Overall, it's a great place to have dinner. Plus, there's a small parking lot outside, but if it's full, parking in general is easier in this area vs the rest of 86th St.

If you love dim sum and can't wake up early for it, just ask and they will steam it right away for you so it taste extra fresh all the way till 3pm! Been going here for awhile now with my family. They dim sum lady remembers exactly what I want and starts putting them on the table before I even get to sit down! Very awesome service. 😊

Came here a couple of times for dim sum. Noteworthy for being one of the few places in NYC (that I've found) that serves baked liu sha bo.  However, the actual dim sum itself is not flavorful. There are far tastier options in the area.  Plus, the service is abysmal. Staff yelled at us rudely demanding tips when we asked to pay by card, as if we never went to a restaurant in the US before. Of course we know to either leave tip on the table or add to the card.  They do offer dim sum to go. It is a shame their service turns me off or I might come back once in while for the baked liu sha bao.

I was running out of places along 86th to try; just when you think your options have run out, another restaurant pops up.  Gotta love NY.  I've been here for lunch a couple of times, and I have to say it is a sweet deal to order off their lunch specials menu.  It's $5.95 and you get a rather large entree-sized dish of various noodles and rice dishes.  If you happen to be off on a weekday, you can share a dish with two other people and still be full.  I have had the broad noodles with beef, the fried rice with crab meat, and a few dishes of dim sum.  Dim sum is rather limited on weekdays so there wasn't much to choose from.  We ordered the pork spare ribs and shrimp rice noodle.  The pork spare ribs were pretty good.  You'll find that the food isn't too salty here.  I also found it to be a lot less greasy than other dim sum places.  There is truth within the other reviews: it does seem more like a place for elders to gather and chat for hours.  It's also obvious that the new owners didn't bother upgrading the interior.  I mean, what old school Chinese dim sum place is going to sport purple cafe lights and reflective mosaic tiles on the walls, and then have stapled plastic along the tables?  Couple that with an ancient looking rug and it is faced with an identity crisis.  The KTV is really one big TV on the lower level of the restaurant.  They play the China version of The Voice on it; it's rather entertaining.  I will be monopolizing that mic if I find that they play English songs on it as well.  All in all, it's a decent place to share a slow-paced meal over conversation.  The food has the special wok taste and this is most definitely attributed to the chef's skill level.  To a particularly discerning eye, it might need some interior work, but if it isn't broke, why fix it?
